# Security Baseline (always on)

## Secrets — zero tolerance
- NEVER hardcode API keys, tokens, passwords, or connection strings in source code — not even "temporarily", not even in examples. Use environment variables / secret managers, and reference `.env.example` with placeholder values.
- Never write real secrets into README, comments, tests, or committed config. If I paste a secret to you, use it via env, don't embed it.
- `.env`, credentials, and key files belong in `.gitignore` — verify before committing.

## Injection — the classics still work
- SQL: parameterized queries only.
- HTML/DOM: escape or use `textContent`; never interpolate untrusted data into `innerHTML`/templates.
- Shell: no string-concatenated commands with user input; use argument arrays / spawn APIs.
- Paths: validate and normalize any user-supplied file path; reject traversal (`..`).

## Auth & Access
- Authorization is checked server-side on every request — hiding a button is not access control.
- Compare secrets with constant-time comparison; hash passwords with bcrypt/argon2 (never MD5/SHA alone, never reversible).
- Sessions/tokens: httpOnly + secure cookies where applicable, short-lived tokens, real logout invalidation.

## Data
- Collect and log the minimum. No PII in logs, URLs, or error messages shown to users.
- Anything user-uploaded is untrusted: validate type/size server-side, store outside the web root, serve with safe content types.

## Dependencies & Supply Chain
- No installing packages from unofficial registries or typo-adjacent names — verify exact package names.
- Treat postinstall scripts and curl-pipe-to-shell instructions with suspicion; surface them to me instead of running silently.

## When touching security-relevant code
Flag it explicitly in your response ("⚠️ security-relevant change") so I review it with more care. Never weaken existing checks (CORS wildcards, disabled TLS verification, relaxed CSP) as a debugging shortcut without a loud warning and a revert plan.
